64 Let not mortals take the vow lightly; 65 be faithful, and to do it not deceitful, 66 as Jephthah to his first offering;
67 to whom it would be more fitting to say ‘I did badly,’ 68 than, by keeping [his vow], to do worse; and thus foolish 69 you can find the great duke of the Greeks,
70 because of whom Iphigenia wept her beautiful face, 71 and made weep both the foolish and the wise 72 who heard speak of such a cultivated act.

